dharma Left for the East? -- t14. An Inconvenient Truth: Science and Argumentation in the Expository Documentary Film -- t15. Planet in Focus: Environmental Film Festivals -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aEnvironmentalism and ecology are areas of rapid growth in academia and society at large. Screening Nature is the first comprehensive work that groups together the wide range of concerns in the field of cinema and the environment, and what could be termed "posthuman cinema." It comprises key readings that highlight the centrality of nature and nonhuman animals to the cinematic medium, and to the language and institution of film. The book offers a fresh and timely intervention into contemporary film theory through a focus on the nonhuman environment as principal register in many filmic texts. Screening Nature offers an extensive resource for teachers, undergraduate students, and more advanced scholars on the intersections between the natural world and the worlds of film. It emphasizes the cross-cultural and geographically diverse relevance of the topic of cinema ecology.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aArmatage, Kay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, James Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Chia-ju, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEastwood, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomel, Elana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc